english:
  title: On Dispelling Suspicion
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: "When people suspect you of something you did not do, it seems right to defend yourself. Yet there are cases where defense is unnecessary—for haste only deepens suspicion. Better to wait with patience, and the truth will untangle itself.\n\nThere was a nursemaid in a household who fell with child while nursing her master's son. When her mistress discovered this, she prepared to beat her, saying: \"The law of nursing forbids contact with men, lest the nursemaid's pregnancy harm the child in her care. This is your first offense. From the day you became nursemaid, not one foot was to cross the threshold—day and night you were to hold and carry the child within these walls. Yet you dared to lie with a man. This is your second offense.\"\n\nThe frightened maid, in her confusion, pointed to her master himself. The mistress fell silent and said no more.\n\nNow it happened the master had been traveling abroad and returned after half a year. Hearing these words, he said: \"I do not approach even women of beauty—how could I approach you? Yet I will not lower myself to argue the matter with you.\" And he said nothing more.\n\nThe maid never confessed, the mistress's suspicion was never resolved, yet the master remained unmoved.\n\nWhen I heard this tale, I offered this interpretation: Even if the maid had confessed her innocence, the mistress's suspicion would not have lifted. The master was right to remain steadfast. Consider the case of Zhi Bu Yi, who once repaid another man's lost gold on his roommate's behalf. Did he do this expecting that the true thief would later return it, thus clearing his name? No—his intention was this: \"Men suspect me because my conduct has not earned their trust. I know well the anguish of indignation, the urge to cry out, to seek judgment from magistrates and appeal to heaven. Yet I would rather bear false shame outwardly while cultivating true virtue within. When this virtue accumulates and manifests, all men will believe with their hearts. Even should I have committed theft before, my uprightness today covers the failings of yesterday. How much more when I am innocent?\"\n\nThis is why the ancients prized self-examination. When a man examines himself and finds faith within, heaven and earth, spirits and gods will trust him. What need has he to fear the judgment of men?\n\nYet among false accusations, some need not be answered, and some cannot be answered no matter what. If one is accused of beating his wife's father, proof of the wife's non-existence clears the charge. If one is accused of murder by Zengzi, proof that one is not truly Zengzi resolves the matter. But there are accusations that are easy to hear, difficult to answer, and only grow more tangled in the answering—these concern deception and theft. Thus lawmakers forbid the mere investigation of rumors heard by ear and doubted in heart. Yet what law can suppress the doubts that lodge in people's minds? Sometimes it is better to remain silent.\n\nZhi Bu Yi made no defense, though truly innocent, and the universe blessed him when the real thief returned the gold. The gold's owner was left speechless with shame, unable to face the world, while Zhi Bu Yi's quiet virtue became renowned and entered the chronicles. The master's conduct in this case was similar.\n\nBut I despise the maid's scheme—she sought to escape punishment by casting blame upon her master. This is a lesson for all servants and dependents. For the duty of maid to mistress, child to parent, subject to ruler, is one and the same.\n\nThe ancient Su Qin told this tale: \"A man's wife took a lover while he served as an official in a distant place. When her husband's return drew near, the lover grew anxious. The wife said, 'Fear not—I have prepared poisoned wine to receive him.' Three days later the husband arrived. The wife sent a maidservant to offer him the cup. The maid, caught between two terrors—fearing to speak lest her mistress be cast out, fearing to remain silent lest her master die—deliberately stumbled and spilled the wine. The master, enraged, beat the maid fifty times.\" This is what happens when loyalty becomes a crime against one's superiors.\n\nBut this maid sought to escape punishment through falsehood and sought to sow discord between master and mistress. How fearful is the heart of the base! \n\nMy friend, the master of this house, belongs to one of the great families of the three kingdoms and goes by the name of the Master of Yangpo. We are well acquainted, and both dwell now in the capital. In the course of our conversation, this matter arose. After our laughter had subsided, I composed this piece, drawing upon Su Qin's words as a lesson for all who serve."
  footnotes:
    - Zhi Bu Yi (直不疑) was a virtuous official in ancient China known for his integrity. The story refers to him repaying lost gold that belonged to a guest in his home, asking no questions despite suspicion.
    - The references to accusations against a man without a wife and to Zengzi are classical examples from Chinese jurisprudence illustrating accusations that are easily proven false.
    - Su Qin (蘇秦) was an ancient Chinese persuader and diplomat whose name became synonymous with eloquence and wisdom.
    - Yangpo (陽坡) was the pen name of the master whom Lee Gok knew—a member of the Korean gentry.
